shared_text:
Webster Police Department, New York
September 9 at 2:51 PM ¬∑

For anyone who lives near any of our schools or drives past any of our schools on their morning after afternoon commutes, please read below for an important traffic advisory starting tomorrow morning at about 7:30 AM.

Webster Central School District schools will be opening tomorrow morning, Thursday, Sept 10. Due to new COVID guidelines and safety measures now in place, we expect more parents will be dropping their children off / picking their children up via private vehicle rather than relying on district school buses. This will probably result in significant traffic congestion at or nearby our schools buildings during AM drop off times and PM pick up times.

If your commute goes past one of our schools, please consider an alternate route to avoid likely delays in and around school zones.

We don't know what to expect, but we are hoping for minimal delays for commuters. There is, however, a real possibility of significant traffic congestion and delays.

We hope everyone has a great first day of school.

post_text:
This is the last week that the Chromebook Repair Center is open before it briefly closes to relocate. Stop by Wednesday or Friday, 9-11AM at the back of Willink Middle School (follow the signs) through August 28. After then the tech staff will take a brief hiatus. It will reopen at Webster Schroeder High School in the main entrance vestibule on Tuesday, September 8. Hours will be Mondays, Tuesdays, and Thursdays, 7:30 a.m. - 3:30p.m.; Wednesdays, 11:00 a.m. - 7:00 p.m.; and Fridays, 8:00 a.m. - 2:00 p.m. Families may also call 265-6400, extension 2 for device support.
Students are encouraged to make sure their Chromebook is charged and properly working before school starts Thursday, September 10.
Elementary students and new secondary students will receive their devices in the first days of school. Details are being worked on now to provide devices to new students who are taking part in the 100% remote plan; stay tuned!

post_text:
All Webster CSD students and staff are required to wear masks during the school day. Gaiter masks do not meet the requirements. Please help your child to remember his/her mask each day. The CDC shares these handy door hangers. You can put one on the door as a visual reminder before you leave to grab that mask!

We recommend that your child practices wearing a mask now, so that he/she is prepared to wear a mask while riding the bus and when at school.

Just sent this calendar project to press today! This labor of love for the Webster PTSA (my second year of donating the design) involves working with a large collection of supplied student artwork, optimizing and organizing images, paying close attention to season and color scheme, while working each page as a puzzle to make the images fit. It's a wonderful piece for the community, and a welcome annual tradition. I always marvel at the talent of the students across the district! To view more of my work, visit jancunninghamdesign.com

Common Sense Media‚Äôs latest report Tweens, Teens, Tech & Mental Health provides guidance to identify adolescents who may be most vulnerable, while acknowledging the critical importance of technology for teens, especially during the COVID-19 pandemic.

The report convenes leading child advocates and stakeholders, including Geoffrey Canada, of Harlem Children's Zone, Jennifer Siebel Newsom, Andrew Yang, and others, with essays that define and demand the support needed to help children recover.

post_text:
Webster CSD parents/guardians who have not yet filled out the survey as to whether your child will participate in 100% remote learning AND whether transportation is required for your child this September, check your IC Parent/Student Portal accounts. You were just sent a reminder message with a link to the survey. The district has extended the deadline for all parents/guardians to complete this important survey to WEDNESDAY, August 12 (TOMORROW at 11:59 p.m.). As a reminder, we need to hear from every parent/guardian regarding your plans for 100% remote learning and transportation FOR EACH OF YOUR SCHOOL-AGE CHILDREN! Knowing our remote learning and transportation choices is critical as bus routing needs to be completed and shared with families.
Thank you in advance for taking a few minutes to complete this important survey.

August 10 at 7:00 AM ¬∑

Meet Maria Rigillo, retired educator and current BOE member. She joined WHEN:DFCC because "It is crucial to educate children, parents and our community on the potential short and long-term effects and negative impacts of substance use and abuse in order to prevent potential injuries and fatalities. Providing mental and emotional alternatives to drug abuse through education can help prevent experimentation and death." Follow us to meet more WHEN:DFCC members and learn about our work! #MeetOurMembers

post_text: New York State Department of Education requires all school-age students age 5-6 (in the given school year) and older be registered in some sort of education program in the district in which they live. This includes students who will be attending public school, those who will be going to private and parochial schools, those who have moved into a new school district, and those who will be homeschooled. (These can be changed at any time, but prior registration is still required.) Webster CSD families whose students are not yet registered may register now. Download registration packets by visiting websterschools.org/registration.

WCSD Daily Meal Service Extended Through Summer!

Webster CSD‚Äôs Food Service Department will continue to provide drive-thru style meals throughout the summer months. PLEASE NOTE that meal service will continue until Tuesday, June 30. Following a brief break in service, drive-thru meals will resume on Monday, July 13, and run through Friday, August 21. Meals will be served weekdays from 8:00 -10:00 a.m. at the back gym entrance of Webster Schroeder High School, 875 Ridge Road.

Families will receive breakfast and lunch at the same time for any student living in Webster CSD, including UPK students. Children do not need to be present in the car to receive meals. Families will stay in their cars and staff will hand meals to you.

Registration is open for kindergarteners and students grades 1-12 who are new to Webster CSD! Parents go to www.websterschools.org/registration to download a registration packet.
The safest method to submit registration paperwork is online, however, the district understands that this is not a possibility for all parents/guardians at this time. Therefore, completed registration forms will be accepted at Webster CSD's registration office located at the Webster Towne Center Plaza, Suite 100, 1028 Ridge Road, Webster. (Located is next to Empire Visionworks, GNC and is the old Peaches restaurant location.)
Please do not drop off any original documentation; copies will only be accepted. Student Registration staff members will reach out via email or telephone with any follow-up questions regarding submitted registration paperwork. Email Carla Watkins, District Registrar, with any questions: carla_watkins@webstercsd.org.

post_text: Governor Andrew Cuomo issued Executive Order 202.39 addressing several topics, including school budget votes. Per the executive order, school districts are required to accept all absentee ballots received by mail through June 16. Districts are not permitted to accept ballots through alternative means such as drop off boxes after 5PM on June 9. Any receptacles used for the hand delivery of ballots must be closed and secured at that time.

post_text: Congratulations to Jacqueline of Spry Middle School! She is one of 30 Spry eighth graders who participated in February in the American Scholastic Achievement League (ASAL) Contest. This national event sponsors separate contests for sixth and eighth grade students, and 11,000 students across the country participated in the eighth grade competition. Jacqueline earned the highest score in New York State from among 36 different schools that participated; she will receive a trophy for that distinction. This is the first time Spry has had an eighth grade state champion; the Warriors have had two sixth grade champions in previous years.
